package lenses

import "github.com/sw6n297mn8-maker/mesh-spec/architecture/artifact-schemas:artifact_schemas"

internationalizationAndLocalizationArchitecture: artifact_schemas.#AnalyticalLens & {
id:     "lens-internationalization-and-localization-architecture"
name:   "Internacionalização e Arquitetura de Localização"

purpose: "Orientar decisões sobre como projetar abstrações que permitem expansão geográfica sem rewrite — Money type, TaxId, BusinessCalendar e RegulationEngine."
status: "draft"

trigger: {
	conditions: [
		"a decisão envolve como projetar o sistema para suportar múltiplos países, moedas, idiomas ou regimes regulatórios no futuro",
		"a decisão envolve se primitivas do domínio (moeda, CNPJ, FIDC, nota fiscal) devem ser abstraídas ou podem ser hardcoded para Brasil",
		"a decisão envolve como representar moeda de forma que suporte multi-currency no futuro sem rewrite",
		"a decisão envolve como projetar identificadores fiscais/tributários de forma genérica (CNPJ é instância de tax_id, não primitiva)",
		"a decisão envolve como strings de interface são gerenciadas para suportar tradução futura",
		"a decisão envolve como regras de negócio variam por jurisdição (regulação, tributação, calendário de feriados, dias úteis)",
		"a decisão envolve trade-offs entre abstração prematura (i18n antes de ter segundo país) e custo de retrofit (refazer quando expandir)",
		"a decisão envolve como formatos locais (data, número, endereço, telefone) são tratados no sistema",
	]
	keywords: [
		"internacionalização", "internationalization", "i18n",
		"localização", "localization", "l10n", "locale",
		"multi-currency", "moeda", "currency", "câmbio", "exchange rate",
		"multi-country", "país", "country", "jurisdição", "jurisdiction",
		"idioma", "language", "tradução", "translation",
		"CNPJ", "RUT", "CUIT", "NIT", "RFC", "tax ID", "identificador fiscal",
		"FIDC", "fideicomiso", "securitización", "factoring",
		"nota fiscal", "factura", "invoice",
		"feriado", "holiday", "business day", "dia útil",
		"formato", "format", "date format", "number format", "address",
		"América Latina", "LATAM", "expansão", "expansion",
		"abstração", "abstraction", "hardcoded", "generic",
	]
	excludeWhen: [
		"a decisão é sobre compliance regulatória no Brasil especificamente — usar regulatory-compliance-as-architecture",
		"a decisão é sobre formatação de números em UI (typography, tabular figures) — usar typographic-systems-for-dense-interfaces",
		"a decisão é sobre modelagem temporal (D+0, settlement) — usar temporal-modeling-for-financial-systems",
		"a decisão é sobre pricing strategy — usar pricing-and-monetization-architecture",
	]
	rationale: "A ambição da Mesh é ser a maior empresa da América Latina. Isso significa: múltiplas moedas (BRL, COP, MXN, ARS, PEN, CLP), múltiplos regimes regulatórios (Bacen/CVM Brasil, SFC Colombia, CNBV Mexico, BCRA Argentina), múltiplos idiomas (pt-BR, es-CO, es-MX), múltiplos formatos fiscais (CNPJ, NIT, RFC, CUIT, RUT) coexistindo. Essa decisão é arquitetural e extremamente cara de retrofit. Se o agente constrói o ECL assumindo BRL como tipo primitivo (currency = decimal, implicitamente BRL), CNPJ como campo text com validação hardcoded, e regras de FIDC como constantes globais: cada expansão geográfica vira rewrite. RC trata regulação brasileira. TS trata formatação pt-BR. TM tratará calendário. Esta lens cobre a decisão arquitetural fundamental: como projetar abstrações que permitem expansão sem rewrite, calibrando entre abstração prematura (overengineering para 5 países quando tem 0 clientes) e custo de retrofit (refazer quando segundo país chegar)."
}

concepts: [
	{
		id:         "il-abstraction-calibration"
		name:       "Calibração de Abstração: Nem Hardcode Tudo, Nem Abstraia Tudo"
		nature:     "theoretical"
		role:       "framework"
		definition: "YAGNI (You Aren't Gonna Need It, Beck 1999): não construa abstração que não precisa hoje. Mas: Lehman's Laws of Software Evolution (1980): programas que são usados devem mudar, e mudanças ficam mais caras com o tempo. Tensão fundamental: abstrair cedo (custo de complexidade hoje sem uso imediato) vs abstrair tarde (custo de retrofit quando necessidade surge). Conceito de 'strategic abstraction' (2024+): nem abstrair tudo (premature generalization — overengineering para cenários que podem nunca acontecer) nem hardcoded tudo (premature specialization — cimentar decisões que são caras de reverter). Para cada conceito do domínio: avaliar: (1) **custo de abstração agora** — complexidade adicional, tempo de desenvolvimento extra, maintenance burden da abstração. (2) **custo de retrofit depois** — quanto custa mudar se não abstrair e precisar depois. Não apenas código: database migrations, API breaking changes, contract updates, agent re-training. (3) **probabilidade de necessidade** — quão provável é que essa abstração será usada em 2-3 anos. Para Mesh com ambição LATAM: alta. Para Mesh sem plano de expansão: baixa. Decision matrix: alto custo de retrofit + alta probabilidade → abstrair agora (worth the upfront cost). Baixo custo de retrofit + baixa probabilidade → hardcode (YAGNI applies). Alto custo de retrofit + probabilidade incerta → prepare 'architectural seam' (2023+). Conceito de 'architectural seam': ponto no código onde futura abstração pode ser inserida com mínimo impacto. Não é a abstração completa — é a preparação. Moeda: em vez de bare decimal para BRL, usar Money type com currency field. Hoje: currency é always 'BRL.' Amanhã: currency pode ser 'COP.' Seam: Money type exists. Custo da seam: minimal (wrapper type, ~4h). Benefício: retrofit de multi-currency é adicionar currency ao enum e configurar per-org, não codebase-wide search-and-replace de todo decimal que é dinheiro."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, calibração por conceito do domínio: **Abstrair agora (alto custo de retrofit + alta probabilidade de necessidade):** (1) **Money type** — {amount: integer_centavos, currency: CurrencyCode}. Custo de abstração: 1 wrapper type com operators, ~4 horas. Custo de retrofit se hardcoded: encontrar TODA ocorrência de decimal/long que representa dinheiro no codebase (centenas de ocorrências em cálculos, database columns, API fields, eventos, UI formatting), converter para Money type, adicionar currency context em toda transação, verificar todo cálculo para currency safety. Custo: 2-3 semanas. Probabilidade: LATAM expansion = COP, MXN, CLP. Alta. Decision: abstrair. (2) **TaxId type** — {value: string, type: TaxIdType, country: CountryCode}. Custo: 1 type + 1 validator interface, ~2-4 horas. Retrofit: renomear 'cnpj' field em 30+ tabelas, add type/country columns, rewrite validation em 15+ places, update API endpoints, update events. Custo: dias a semanas. Probabilidade: LATAM = NIT, RFC, CUIT. Alta. Decision: abstrair. (3) **Locale context** — {country: CountryCode, language: LanguageCode, timezone: Timezone}. Propagado em toda request via middleware. Custo: 1 context object + middleware, ~2 horas. Retrofit: adicionar locale context retroativamente em toda request handling chain. Custo: significativo (touches every handler). Decision: abstrair. **Preparar seam (alto retrofit + probabilidade incerta):** (4) **Regulatory rules** — interface RegulationEngine com implementation BrazilRegulation. Custo: 1 interface + 1 implementation (mesma complexidade que hardcoded — business logic vai para o implementation ao invés de estar inline). Retrofit sem interface: extrair rules hardcoded de business logic espalhado pelo codebase inteiro para uma interface. Custo: alto (rules estão em 20+ arquivos em if/else blocks). Decision: seam (interface from day 1). (5) **Invoice/document types** — interface TaxDocumentProcessor com NotaFiscalBrasileira implementation. Seam: adicionar FacturaColombia sem mudar processing pipeline. Retrofit: alto (pipeline inteiro assumes NF-e XML structure). Decision: seam. **Hardcode (baixo retrofit OU baixa probabilidade a curto prazo):** (6) **UI strings** — pt-BR hardcoded no código. Tradução futura: integrar i18n library (react-intl), extrair strings para files, traduzir. Custo de retrofit: moderado (~40-60h para extraction + library integration). Probabilidade de segundo idioma em 1-2 anos: baixa (mercado é 100% brasileiro). Decision: hardcode now, prepare naming discipline for future extraction. (7) **Address format** — formato brasileiro (CEP, UF, cidade, bairro, rua, número). Retrofit: moderado (add country-specific formatting). Probabilidade: quando expandir. Decision: hardcode now."
		meshImplication: "Implementation rules: (1) **Money type from day 1 — não negociável.** Todo valor monetário no sistema: Money(amount, currency). Cálculos: operações na Money type que validam same currency. Database: columns amount BIGINT + currency CHAR(3). API: {amount: 4875000, currency: 'BRL'} (integer centavos + ISO 4217 code). Se agente cria campo 'valor NUMERIC(15,2)' sem currency companion: flag — 'use Money type.' CLAUDE.md: 'todo valor monetário: Money(amount, currency). Nunca decimal/numeric/long sozinho para dinheiro. Database: BIGINT + CHAR(3) currency.' (2) **TaxId type from day 1.** TaxId(value, type, country). Validação: TaxIdValidator interface com CnpjValidator implementation. Se agente cria campo 'cnpj TEXT' ou 'cnpj VARCHAR(14)': flag — 'use TaxId type.' Database: tax_id VARCHAR(20) + tax_id_type VARCHAR(10) + country CHAR(2). API: {tax_id: {value: '12345678000195', type: 'CNPJ', country: 'BR'}}. (3) **Locale context propagada.** Middleware: toda request carrega locale {country: 'BR', language: 'pt-BR', timezone: 'America/Sao_Paulo'}. Default: BR. Futuramente: derivada de org.country config. Formatters: consomem locale da request. (4) **Interfaces para regulatory + documents.** RegulationEngine interface + BrazilRegulation implementation. TaxDocumentProcessor interface + NotaFiscalProcessor implementation. Consumer code: depende de interface, não de implementation. Adicionar país: nova implementation. Consumer: zero change. (5) **UI strings: hardcode now, prepare later.** Strings em pt-BR no código. Disciplina: frases completas (não concatenação), sem idiomas intraduzíveis, placeholders com {named_params}. Quando segundo idioma for 6 meses away: (a) integrar react-intl/next-intl. (b) extract strings para /locales/pt-BR.json. (c) translate to es-CO. (d) language toggle per user/org. Estimated effort: 40-60h. (6) **Seam documentation no mesh-spec.** /foundations/i18n-seams.md: lista de seams, implementação atual, como estender para novo país. Agente que precisa expandir: lê seam guide, implementa. Anti-pattern: 'const MOEDA = BRL' como constante global usada em 200 arquivos — quando Colombia: search-replace em 200 + lógica para selecionar moeda + testes para ambas moedas + migration de data + API breaking change. Cost: weeks. vs Money(amount, currency) type desde dia 1: add 'COP' to CurrencyCode enum + configure per org. Cost: hours."
		rationale: "YAGNI Beck 1999. Lehman's Laws 1980. Strategic abstraction 2024+. Architectural seam 2023+. Na Mesh, Money type + TaxId type + Locale context + Regulatory interface: ~16 horas de upfront work que previnem semanas de retrofit na primeira expansão. UI strings hardcoded: acceptable (moderate retrofit, low near-term probability). Calibrated: abstract where retrofit is expensive AND probability is high."
	},
	{
		id:         "il-multi-currency-architecture"
		name:       "Arquitetura Multi-Currency: Dinheiro como Tipo com Moeda Explícita"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "framework"
		reviewCadence: "annual"
		definition: "Multi-currency é a decisão de i18n com maior impacto para fintech: permeia todo o sistema — database schema, business logic, API contracts, UI formatting, reporting, regulatory compliance. Conceito de 'Money as first-class type' (Fowler 2002, Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture — Money pattern): Money = (amount, currency). Operações: add (same currency only — BRL + COP = error, caught at compile or runtime), subtract (same currency), multiply by scalar (R$100 × 2 = R$200), compare (same currency only). Cross-currency: explicit conversion via exchange rate — never implicit. Money(100, BRL) + Money(50, COP) → CurrencyMismatchError (not silent conversion to one currency). This is type safety for money. Conceito de 'currency-aware calculation' (2024+): every financial calculation: (a) receives inputs with explicit currency. (b) validates all inputs are same currency (or explicitly converts with documented rate). (c) produces output with explicit currency. Never: implicit assumption that 'amount is BRL.' If function accepts bare Long/Decimal for money: caller can pass amount in any currency without system knowing — errors are silent and discovered in reconciliation weeks later. Money type: errors are loud and immediate. Conceito de 'exchange rate management' (2024+): when multi-currency is active: exchange rates are: time-variant (rate changes daily or intraday), source-dependent (rate from Banco Central differs from market rate or commercial rate), and operationally critical (wrong rate = financial loss). Rate: fetched from authoritative source, stored with timestamp, applied at moment of transaction, preserved for audit (rate used in operation is recorded, not looked up retroactively). FIDC with multi-currency carteira: consolidated report requires conversion at specific rate on specific date — not 'current rate.'"
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, multi-currency architecture phased: **Phase 1 (now, Brazil-only):** Money type exists: {amount: Long, currency: CurrencyCode}. All operations: BRL. Currency field: present but constant ('BRL'). Database: every monetary column has BIGINT amount + CHAR(3) currency DEFAULT 'BRL'. API: every monetary field returns {amount: 4875000, currency: 'BRL'}. Calculations: Money operations validate same currency (even though today it's always BRL — validation exists, catches bugs like Money(0, null)). If anyone creates Money with unsupported currency: rejected at creation. Formatting: Money.format(locale) → 'R$48.750,00' (locale-aware from day 1). **Phase 2 (expansion to Colombia, first non-BRL):** Add COP to CurrencyCode enum. Org config: {default_currency: 'COP'} for Colombian orgs. Operations: per-org currency. All calculations: same as before (Money operations are already same-currency validated). Colombian org: all operations in COP. Brazilian: BRL. No cross-currency operations initially. NEW: exchange rate service for cross-currency REPORTING. If FIDC has carteira with BRL + COP operations: consolidated report in BRL requires COP→BRL conversion. Rate source: Banco Central do Brasil (for BRL reference rates, published daily). Implementation: ExchangeRateService.convert(money, targetCurrency, date). **Phase 3 (mature, multiple LATAM):** Multiple currencies active simultaneously. Cross-currency operations possible (supply chain spanning countries). FX risk management: rate locked at operation creation time, settlement at locked rate. Rate volatility handling: if rate moves >N% between creation and settlement: policy (proceed at locked rate, or renegotiate). Exchange rate audit: every conversion logged with rate, source, timestamp."
		meshImplication: "Money implementation rules: (1) **Money class/type** — data class Money(val amount: Long, val currency: CurrencyCode). Overloaded operators: plus (validates same currency — throws CurrencyMismatchException if different), minus (validates), times (scalar: Money × Int → Money, Money × Decimal → Money with rounding), compareTo (validates same currency). Factory: Money.of(48750.00, 'BRL') → Money(4875000, CurrencyCode.BRL). Internal: integer centavos (no floating point). toString: 'Money(4875000, BRL)' (technical). format(locale): 'R$48.750,00' (human-readable, locale-aware). (2) **database schema convention** — every monetary column: BIGINT (centavos) + CHAR(3) currency. NOT: NUMERIC(15,2) alone (no currency = implicit BRL = retrofit nightmare). Column names: amount + currency as pair. operations.face_value_amount BIGINT + operations.face_value_currency CHAR(3). Constraint: currency IN (supported currencies). Default: 'BRL'. Migration for existing bare NUMERIC: ALTER ADD currency CHAR(3) DEFAULT 'BRL'. (3) **API contract** — every monetary field in API response: {amount: integer_centavos, currency: 'BRL'}. NOT: {amount: 48750.00} (no currency, floating point). Integer centavos: no precision loss. Currency explicit: no assumption. Request: same format — client sends {amount: 4875000, currency: 'BRL'}. (4) **calculation safety** — Money(100_00, 'BRL') + Money(200_00, 'BRL') = Money(300_00, 'BRL') ✓. Money(100_00, 'BRL') + Money(200_00, 'COP') = CurrencyMismatchException ✗. Caught at: compile time in Kotlin (if CurrencyCode is part of generic type) or runtime (validation in operator). Either way: error is immediate, not silent. (5) **currency-specific configuration** — different currencies: different decimal places. BRL: 2 decimals (centavos). COP: 0 decimals (no centavos in practice). CLP: 0 decimals. JPY: 0 decimals. USD: 2 decimals. Config: CurrencyConfig { code: 'COP', decimalPlaces: 0, symbol: '$', name: 'Peso colombiano' }. Money.of(48750, 'COP') → Money(48750, COP) (no centavos). Formatting: '$48.750' (0 decimals). (6) **exchange rate seam** — interface ExchangeRateService { fun convert(amount: Money, targetCurrency: CurrencyCode, date: LocalDate): Money; fun getRate(from: CurrencyCode, to: CurrencyCode, date: LocalDate): ExchangeRate }. Implementation Phase 1: throws UnsupportedOperationException('multi-currency not yet supported'). Implementation Phase 2: fetches from Banco Central API, caches daily. (7) **CLAUDE.md** — 'every monetary value: Money(amount, currency). Never bare Long, Int, BigDecimal, or Double for money. Database: BIGINT + CHAR(3) currency pair. API: {amount: centavos_int, currency: code}. Calculations: use Money operators (validated same-currency). If you need cross-currency: use ExchangeRateService (Phase 2+).' Anti-pattern: 'valor: 48750.00' in API (no currency — consumer assumes BRL; floating point — precision loss possible). When Colombia: every API consumer must add currency handling. Every database query must add currency filter. Every calculation must add currency validation. Retrofit of bare decimal across entire codebase: 2-3 weeks minimum. vs Money type from day 1: add COP to enum, configure per org, hours of work."
		dependsOn: ["il-abstraction-calibration"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-testing-and-validation-for-financial-systems"
			conceptId: "tv-financial-invariants"
			context:   "TV defines financial invariants including conservation of money (sum of parts = whole). IL multi-currency enriches this invariant: conservation must hold PER CURRENCY. BRL in = BRL out. COP in = COP out. Cross-currency conversion: explicit with preserved rate, and conservation holds in BOTH currencies (amount_source × rate = amount_target). TV says 'sum of parts = whole'; IL says 'sum of parts = whole AND all parts must be same currency AND cross-currency is explicit with auditable rate.' TV property-based tests: enriched with currency validation (generator produces multi-currency scenarios)."
		}]
		rationale: "Fowler 2002: Money pattern. Currency-aware calculation 2024+. Exchange rate management 2024+. Na Mesh, Money type from day 1: ~4 hours to implement (class + database convention + API convention). Retrofit if hardcoded: 2-3 weeks. Ratio: 4h / 80-120h = 3-5% of retrofit cost. Most impactful i18n decision for fintech. Also: Money type provides type safety even in single-currency (prevents adding amount + tax_rate accidentally, prevents bare Long confusion)."
	},
	{
		id:         "il-tax-and-fiscal-identity"
		name:       "Identidade Fiscal e Tributária: CNPJ é Instância, Não Primitiva"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "property"
		reviewCadence: "annual"
		definition: "Cada país da América Latina tem identificador fiscal diferente: Brasil (CNPJ 14 dígitos numéricos com 2 dígitos verificadores), Colombia (NIT 9-10 dígitos com 1 dígito de verificação), México (RFC 12-13 caracteres alfanuméricos), Argentina (CUIT 11 dígitos com formato XX-XXXXXXXX-X), Peru (RUC 11 dígitos), Chile (RUT 8-9 dígitos com dígito verificador que pode ser 'K'). Cada um: formato diferente, algoritmo de validação diferente, API de consulta diferente (Receita Federal Brasil, DIAN Colombia, SAT Mexico), campos de retorno diferentes (razão social, endereço, situação cadastral — formats vary). Conceito de 'tax identifier as pluggable type' (2024+): TaxId = {value: string, type: TaxIdType, country: CountryCode}. Validação: interface TaxIdValidator com implementation per type. CnpjValidator: verifica 14 dígitos + algoritmo de dígitos verificadores + opcionalmente consulta API Receita Federal para status ('ativa', 'inapta', 'suspensa'). NitValidator (Colombia): verifica 9-10 dígitos + dígito de verificação + consulta DIAN. Validators: pluggable. Adicionar país: criar novo validator, registrar. Consumer code: chama taxId.validate() — não sabe qual validator roda internamente. Conceito de 'fiscal document abstraction' (2024+): nota fiscal eletrônica brasileira (NF-e, formato XML com 54 campos obrigatórios, validada pela SEFAZ) ≠ factura eletrônica colombiana (formato UBL 2.1, validada pela DIAN) ≠ CFDI mexicana (formato XML SAT, com complementos). Cada uma: schema diferente, campos diferentes, autoridade diferente, requisitos legais diferentes. Abstração: TaxDocument interface = {type: TaxDocumentType, issuer: TaxId, recipient: TaxId, lineItems: [], total: Money, issueDate: LocalDate, metadata: country_specific_map}. Processing pipeline: consumes TaxDocument interface. Country-specific parsing: adapter per document type que lê formato raw (XML, UBL, PDF) e produz TaxDocument."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, tax identity architecture: **TaxId type:** data class TaxId(val value: String, val type: TaxIdType, val country: CountryCode). Enum TaxIdType: CNPJ, CPF, NIT, RFC, CUIT, RUC, RUT. Validation interface: TaxIdValidator { fun validate(taxId: TaxId): ValidationResult }. Implementation: CnpjValidator (Brazil) — validates format (14 digits), check digits (mod 11 algorithm), optionally queries Receita Federal API for company status. Database: tax_id VARCHAR(20) + tax_id_type VARCHAR(10) + country CHAR(2). NOT: cnpj VARCHAR(14). Migration from existing: RENAME COLUMN cnpj TO tax_id; ADD COLUMN tax_id_type VARCHAR(10) DEFAULT 'CNPJ'; ADD COLUMN country CHAR(2) DEFAULT 'BR'. API: {tax_id: {value: '12.345.678/0001-95', type: 'CNPJ', country: 'BR'}}. NOT: {cnpj: '12345678000195'}. Display: TaxId.format() → 'CNPJ: 12.345.678/0001-95' (formatted with dots, slash, dash per Brazilian convention). Future NIT: 'NIT: 900.123.456-7' (Colombian formatting). **Fiscal documents:** interface TaxDocumentProcessor { fun parse(rawDocument: ByteArray, documentType: TaxDocumentType): TaxDocument; fun validate(doc: TaxDocument): ValidationResult; fun extractFinancials(doc: TaxDocument): ExtractedFinancials }. Implementation: NotaFiscalProcessor (Brazil) — parses NF-e XML, extracts: emitente (issuer), destinatário (recipient), itens, valor total, data de emissão, chave de acesso. Validates: against SEFAZ if needed. Future: FacturaColombiaProcessor — parses UBL 2.1 XML. Same interface, different parsing logic. Consumer: calls processor.parse() + processor.extractFinancials() — doesn't know if it's NF-e or Factura."
		meshImplication: "TaxId implementation: (1) **TaxId from day 1** — replace every 'cnpj' field in database and API with TaxId. Database: 3 columns (value, type, country). API: nested object. Validation: pluggable interface with CnpjValidator. Cost: 2-4 hours for type + validator + migration. (2) **display formatting per type** — TaxId.format() dispatches to formatter per type. CNPJ: '12.345.678/0001-95' (dots, slash, dash). NIT: '900.123.456-7' (dots, dash). RFC: 'ABC123456XY0' (no formatting, alphanumeric). Formatting: never hardcoded in UI components — always TaxId.format(). (3) **external API integration abstraction** — interface TaxAuthorityClient { fun lookup(taxId: TaxId): CompanyInfo }. Implementation: ReceitaFederalClient (Brazil) — queries Receita Federal API by CNPJ, returns: razão social, nome fantasia, situação cadastral, endereço, QSA (quadro de sócios). Future: DianClient (Colombia) — queries DIAN by NIT, returns equivalent Colombian company info. Consumer: calls taxAuthorityClient.lookup(taxId) — doesn't know which country API is queried. (4) **fiscal document pipeline** — upload raw document → detect type (NF-e XML? Factura UBL? PDF?) → route to appropriate TaxDocumentProcessor → parse → extract: issuer TaxId, recipient TaxId, line items, total as Money (with currency!), issue date, document identifier. Pipeline is document-type agnostic. Adding new document type: add parser implementation. Pipeline: unchanged. (5) **CLAUDE.md** — 'identificadores fiscais: use TaxId(value, type, country). NEVER create field named cnpj — use tax_id with type. Validation: use TaxIdValidator interface, not inline regex. When processing documents: use TaxDocumentProcessor interface. When looking up company info: use TaxAuthorityClient interface.' Anti-pattern: 'cnpj' VARCHAR(14) as field name in 30 tables. Colombia arrives: rename all to 'tax_id', add type + country columns to each, change all validations (14-digit regex → pluggable validator), update all API endpoints ({cnpj: '...'} → {tax_id: {value, type, country}}), update all event schemas, update all UI display logic. Regex that validates CNPJ format: hardcoded in 15 places across codebase — replace ALL with pluggable validator. Cost: days to weeks. vs TaxId type from day 1: add NitValidator, register, done. Cost: hours."
		dependsOn: ["il-abstraction-calibration"]
		rationale: "Tax identifier as pluggable type 2024+. Fiscal document abstraction 2024+. Na Mesh, TaxId type: 2-4 hours implementation. Retrofit without it: days to weeks (rename columns, change API contracts, rewrite validators). CNPJ is an instance of TaxId, not the only possible value. Abstraction pays for itself even before expansion: type safety catches 'CNPJ with 13 digits' at validation, not in production."
	},
	{
		id:         "il-locale-aware-formatting"
		name:       "Formatação Locale-Aware: Storage Canônico, Presentation por Contexto Cultural"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "property"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Cada locale tem convenções de formatação distintas: **Números:** pt-BR: 1.234.567,89 (ponto como milhar separator, vírgula como decimal). es-CO: 1.234.567,89 (mesmo). en-US: 1,234,567.89 (invertido). **Datas:** pt-BR: 25/02/2026 (dd/mm/yyyy). en-US: 02/25/2026 (mm/dd/yyyy). ISO 8601: 2026-02-25 (yyyy-mm-dd, unambiguous). **Moeda:** BRL: R$48.750,00 (símbolo antes, ponto milhar, vírgula decimal). COP: $48.750 (sem decimais — COP não usa centavos na prática). USD: $48,750.00 (vírgula milhar, ponto decimal). **Endereço:** Brasil: Rua ABC, 123 — Bairro XYZ, Rio de Janeiro — RJ, 20000-000. Colombia: Calle 123 #45-67, Bogotá, Cundinamarca. **Telefone:** Brasil: +55 (21) 98765-4321 (country code + DDD + number). Colombia: +57 321 8765432 (country code + number, no area code formatting). Conceito de 'locale as runtime context' (2024+): formatação não é hardcoded no código — é derivada do locale da request. Server: armazena dados em formato canônico (ISO 8601 date UTC, integer centavos, structured address object). Presentation layer: formata per locale do user/org. Same data: different visual representation per locale. Server logic: never operates on formatted strings (formatted is lossy — '25/02/2026' string: is it dd/mm or mm/dd? Ambiguous without locale context). Always: operate on typed values (LocalDate, Money, TaxId), format only for display."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, formatting strategy: **Storage (canonical, locale-agnostic — source of truth):** dates: ISO 8601 UTC (TIMESTAMPTZ for events: 2026-03-13T14:30:00Z. DATE for business dates: 2026-03-13). Money: integer centavos + currency code (BIGINT + CHAR(3)). TaxId: raw digits + type + country (VARCHAR + VARCHAR + CHAR). Address: structured object {street: 'Rua ABC', number: '123', complement: 'Sala 1', district: 'Centro', city: 'Rio de Janeiro', state: 'RJ', postal_code: '20000-000', country: 'BR'}. Phone: E.164 format (+5521987654321) stored raw. Timezone: UTC always in storage (events). Business timezone: configured per org/country. **Presentation (locale-aware — for humans):** locale context from request middleware: {country: 'BR', language: 'pt-BR', timezone: 'America/Sao_Paulo'}. formatDate(date, locale) → '25/02/2026' (pt-BR) or '02/25/2026' (en-US). formatMoney(money, locale) → 'R$48.750,00' (BRL, pt-BR) or '$48.750' (COP, es-CO). formatTaxId(taxId) → '12.345.678/0001-95' (CNPJ) or '900.123.456-7' (NIT). formatPhone(phone, locale) → '(21) 98765-4321' (Brazil) or '321 876 5432' (Colombia). formatAddress(address, locale) → full formatted address per country convention."
		meshImplication: "Formatting implementation: (1) **canonical storage — non-negotiable rules.** Dates: TIMESTAMPTZ for events/actions (UTC, moment in time). DATE for business dates (no timezone — date IS the value, per TM lens). Money: BIGINT centavos + CHAR(3) currency. Never store formatted values (formatted is lossy, locale-specific, non-calculable). If any column stores '25/02/2026' as VARCHAR: flag — should be DATE. If any column stores 'R$48.750,00' as VARCHAR: flag — should be BIGINT + CHAR(3). (2) **Intl API for formatting** — use platform Intl APIs: JavaScript: Intl.NumberFormat('pt-BR', {style: 'currency', currency: 'BRL'}). Kotlin: java.text.NumberFormat.getCurrencyInstance(Locale('pt', 'BR')). Java.time: DateTimeFormatter.ofLocalizedDate(FormatStyle.SHORT).withLocale(locale). DON'T handcode formatting (manual string concatenation of 'R$' + formatted number: breaks for COP, USD, etc). Intl handles: symbol placement, milhar separator, decimal separator, decimal places per currency. (3) **locale propagation** — middleware: every request: extract locale from: (a) user profile preference (if set). (b) org default (country of org). (c) Accept-Language header. (d) default ('pt-BR'). Set in request context. All formatters: read from context. No formatter: hardcodes 'pt-BR'. (4) **timezone handling** — UTC everywhere in backend and database. Display: converted to user's timezone from locale context. API: accept UTC input, return UTC output (ISO 8601 with Z). Frontend: convert to display timezone for UI. Rule: UTC in all layers except final presentation. Server code: never uses LocalDateTime.now() without explicit zone. (5) **address as structured object** — {street, number, complement, district, city, state, postal_code, country}. NOT free-text string ('Rua ABC, 123, Centro, RJ' — not parseable, not searchable by component, not formattable per country). Structured: validatable (postal_code format per country), formattable per convention, searchable (city='Rio de Janeiro'). (6) **CLAUDE.md** — 'dates: store as UTC (TIMESTAMPTZ) or DATE. Display: format per locale using Intl API. Money: store as BIGINT + CHAR(3). Display: Intl.NumberFormat per locale. Addresses: structured object, not free-text. Phone: E.164 stored, formatted per locale for display. Never store formatted values in database. Never hardcode locale-specific formatting in business logic.' Anti-pattern: storing dates as '25/02/2026' VARCHAR string — is this dd/mm/yyyy (pt-BR) or mm/dd/yyyy (en-US)? Ambiguous without locale metadata. When Colombia: Colombian user sees '25/02/2026' → interprets as dd/mm (same as pt-BR, ok). US partner sees same → interprets as mm/dd → wrong date. If stored as DATE 2026-02-25: unambiguous, formattable per any locale."
		dependsOn: ["il-abstraction-calibration", "il-multi-currency-architecture"]
		rationale: "Locale as runtime context 2024+. Na Mesh, canonical storage (UTC, centavos, structured) + locale-aware presentation = same data renders correctly in any locale. Cost of locale-aware formatting from start: minimal (use Intl APIs — they exist, they're free, they handle edge cases). Cost of retrofit: moderate (find every hardcoded format string, replace with Intl call, verify per locale). Benefit even in single-locale: Intl handles edge cases (negative numbers, zero, large numbers) better than manual formatting."
	},
	{
		id:         "il-regulatory-jurisdiction-abstraction"
		name:       "Abstração de Jurisdição Regulatória: Regras de Negócio por País, Não Hardcoded"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "annual"
		definition: "Cada país LATAM tem regulatory framework diferente para operações financeiras e supply chain: Brasil (Bacen para sistema financeiro + CVM para mercado de capitais/FIDC + LGPD para dados), Colombia (SFC Superintendencia Financiera + Fondo de inversión colectivo como veículo + Ley 1581/2012 para dados), México (CNBV Comisión Nacional Bancaria + Sofom como veículo + LFPDPPP para dados), Argentina (BCRA + Fideicomiso financiero + Ley 25.326 para dados). Regras variam por país: taxas máximas permitidas, documentos obrigatórios para compliance, reporting requirements (periodicidade, formato, destinatário), investor protection rules, AML thresholds, KYC/KYB requirements (documentos, verificações, periodicidade de renovação). Conceito de 'jurisdiction as configuration' (2024+): regras regulatórias são configuração por jurisdição, não lógica hardcoded. Interface RegulationEngine com: getRequiredDocuments(country, entityType) → List<ComplianceRequirement>, getMaxRate(country, operationType) → Decimal?, getReportingRequirements(country, vehicleType) → List<ReportSchedule>, getKycRequirements(country, entityType) → List<KycCheck>, getFundingVehicleRules(country) → FundingRules. Brazil implementation: required_docs = ['certidão negativa', 'FGTS', 'INSS'], reporting = ['mensal CVM', 'diário Bacen se aplicável'], kyc = ['CNPJ ativo', 'QSA', 'sócios sem restrição'], funding_vehicle = 'FIDC'. Colombia implementation: different values, same interface. Consumer code: calls regulationEngine.getRequiredDocuments(org.country, ...) — doesn't know which country. Conceito de 'regulatory feature flags' (2024+): novo requisito regulatório como feature flag per country. Brasil introduz nova regra de reporting FIDC: flag 'br_new_fidc_reporting_2026'. Enabled: para orgs brasileiras quando regulação entra em vigor. Doesn't affect: Colombian orgs. Gradual compliance: enable para orgs conforme se preparam."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, regulatory abstraction: **Interface:** RegulationEngine { fun getComplianceRequirements(country: CountryCode, entityType: EntityType): List<ComplianceRequirement>. fun validateOperation(operation: Operation, country: CountryCode): ValidationResult. fun getReportingSchedule(country: CountryCode, vehicleType: VehicleType): List<ReportSchedule>. fun getFundingVehicleRules(country: CountryCode): FundingRules. fun getKycRequirements(country: CountryCode, entityType: EntityType): List<KycCheck>. }. **Brazil implementation:** BrazilRegulationEngine. Requirements: compliance per Bacen + CVM. Funding vehicle: FIDC (Fundo de Investimento em Direitos Creditórios — regulated by CVM). Required documents: certidão negativa federal, FGTS regularidade, INSS regularidade, contrato social atualizado. Score constraints: none regulatory (internal policy). Reporting: mensal CVM (informe mensal de FIDC), trimestral (demonstrações financeiras). KYC: CNPJ ativo na Receita, QSA sem PEP não declarada, sócios sem restrições em bases restritivas. **Seam for expansion:** interface exists. Adding Colombia: create ColombiaRegulationEngine. Configure: funding vehicle = Fondo de inversión colectivo. Required docs: certificado de existencia y representación legal, estados financieros auditados, RUT actualizado. Reporting: SFC requirements (periodicidade e formato colombianos). KYC: NIT verificado na DIAN, representante legal sem reportes. Consumer code (compliance check, operation validation, report generation): calls regulationEngine.getX(org.country) — doesn't know which country. Polymorphism handles routing."
		meshImplication: "Regulatory implementation: (1) **RegulationEngine interface from day 1** — defined in mesh-spec as contract. Per-country implementation. Even with only Brazil: code calls regulationEngine.getComplianceRequirements('BR', ...) instead of hardcoding require(certidaoNegativa). Same effort for single country (logic goes into implementation instead of inline). Payoff: second country is additive. (2) **country-org binding** — each org: has country field. Country determines which: RegulationEngine implementation, TaxIdValidator, TaxDocumentProcessor, BusinessCalendar, locale default. Org.country is the dispatch key for all jurisdiction-specific behavior. (3) **regulatory rules as configuration where possible** — within each country implementation: rules as config (JSON, CUE, or constants file) rather than imperative code. { required_documents: ['certidao_negativa', 'fgts', 'inss'], kyc_checks: ['cnpj_ativo', 'qsa_sem_restricao'], reporting: [{type: 'monthly_cvm', format: 'xml', deadline_bd: 5}], max_rate: null }. Config change (new document requirement): update config, no code change, no deploy. Imperative logic (complex validation, conditional requirements): in code within implementation. (4) **regulatory feature flags** — new requirement: flag per country. 'br_new_fidc_reporting_2026': preview (FIDC can test), enforcement (required). Colombian orgs: unaffected. Flag management: same as PE lens feature flags. (5) **testing per jurisdiction** — each country implementation: tested independently with country-specific test data. Brazil tests: validate against Brazilian rules. Colombia tests: validate against Colombian rules. Cross-country test: operation with BR org uses BR rules; operation with CO org uses CO rules. Adding Colombia: Brazil tests MUST continue passing (regression). (6) **CLAUDE.md** — 'regulatory rules: in RegulationEngine implementation per country. NEVER hardcode regulatory rule directly in business logic (ComplianceService, OperationService, etc.). Call regulationEngine.getX(country). When implementing new regulatory requirement: add to country config/implementation, not to global business logic. If unsure which country a rule applies to: make it country-specific (err toward jurisdiction-scoped, not global).' Anti-pattern: 'if (operation.tipo == ANTECIPACAO) { require(certidaoNegativa); require(fgts); require(inss); }' hardcoded in ComplianceService.kt line 47. When Colombia arrives: (a) these documents don't exist in Colombia. (b) can't add Colombian requirements to same block (different entity, different validations). (c) must fork ComplianceService into per-country branches OR add if(country == BR) { ... } else if(country == CO) { ... } chains that grow linearly with countries. vs RegulationEngine: ComplianceService calls regulationEngine.getRequirements(country) → gets list → validates each. Adding country: new implementation. ComplianceService: zero changes."
		dependsOn: ["il-abstraction-calibration"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-regulatory-compliance-as-architecture"
			conceptId: "rc-compliance-by-design"
			context:   "RC defines compliance-by-design: regulatory requirements embedded in architecture, not bolted on. IL extends to multi-jurisdiction: compliance-by-design PER COUNTRY via RegulationEngine interface. RC says 'embed compliance in architecture'; IL says 'abstract compliance per jurisdiction so that adding country = adding implementation, not rewriting architecture.' RC is compliance depth within 1 jurisdiction; IL is compliance breadth across N jurisdictions. Together: deeply compliant in each jurisdiction AND abstractly extensible for new ones."
		}]
		rationale: "Jurisdiction as configuration 2024+. Regulatory feature flags 2024+. Na Mesh, RegulationEngine interface: ~8 hours for interface + Brazil implementation (same effort as hardcoded — logic just goes into implementation instead of inline). Retrofit without interface: extracting hardcoded rules from business logic scattered across 20+ files into a coherent interface. Cost: weeks. Interface from day 1: second country is additive, not extractive."
	},
	{
		id:         "il-string-externalization"
		name:       "Externalização de Strings: Preparar para Multi-Language sem Implementar Agora"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "heuristic"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Full i18n of UI strings is expensive: extract all user-facing strings from components, create translation files per locale, integrate i18n library (react-intl, next-intl, i18next), translate (professional translation for financial/legal content), test in each language (layout, truncation, RTL if applicable). Premature for platform with 0 non-Portuguese users and no concrete expansion timeline. Conceito de 'i18n readiness without i18n implementation' (2024+): prepare architecture for translation without actually translating. This means: (1) **naming discipline** — UI strings are complete sentences with named placeholders, not concatenated fragments. 'Operação {id} aprovada em {date}' NOT 'Operação ' + id + ' aprovada em ' + date. Concatenation breaks in languages where word order differs (Japanese: date comes before id). Named placeholders: i18n library substitutes per locale. (2) **no UI logic in strings** — 'Você tem {count} operação(ões) pendente(s)' — pluralization is locale-dependent (Portuguese: singular/plural. Arabic: singular/dual/plural. Japanese: no plural). Use: ICU MessageFormat or pluralization library when i18n is implemented. For now: write strings that are complete and extractable. (3) **seam for extraction** — user-facing strings in component files (acceptable for single language) but following patterns that enable extraction. When extraction happens: grep for string patterns, replace with t('key') calls. If strings follow discipline: extraction is mechanical. If concatenated/fragmented: extraction is rewrite. (4) **content vs code** — user-facing text (labels, messages, errors, notifications) separate from technical strings (log messages, variable names, internal comments). Technical: always English (developers read code in English). User-facing: locale-dependent (today: pt-BR hardcoded. Tomorrow: per locale). Conceito de 'translation-ready architecture' (2024+): when second language is 6 months away: (1) integrate i18n library. (2) extract strings to .json files per locale. (3) translate. (4) deploy with language toggle. Architecture: ready. Translation: invested when justified by concrete expansion plan."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, string strategy: **Now (pt-BR only, no i18n library):** all UI strings in pt-BR. Organized: in component files. Naming discipline: complete sentences with placeholders. 'Operação #{id} aprovada pela construtora {construtora_name} em {date}.' Not: 'Operação #' + id + ' aprovada pela construtora ' + name + ' em ' + formatDate(date). Error messages: specific and complete (from IP lens feedback patterns). 'CNPJ inválido — verifique os dígitos verificadores (esperado: 14 dígitos numéricos).' **Seam (preparation without investment):** API error codes: machine-readable (error_code: 'TAX_ID_INVALID'). Human message: locale-dependent (today hardcoded pt-BR, tomorrow per locale). API returns: {error_code: 'TAX_ID_INVALID', message: 'CNPJ inválido — verifique os dígitos verificadores.', details: {field: 'tax_id', expected_format: 'XX.XXX.XXX/XXXX-XX'}}. Consumer: uses code for logic, message for display. When i18n: message is generated per locale from code + details. Email/notification templates: separate files per locale path. /templates/pt-BR/operation_approved.html. When i18n: /templates/es-CO/operation_approved.html. Template engine: loads per locale. **When second language needed (6 months before launch):** (1) integrate react-intl (or next-intl, i18next — whichever fits stack). (2) extract strings from components to /locales/pt-BR.json: {'operation.approved': 'Operação #{id} aprovada pela construtora {name} em {date}'}. (3) create /locales/es-CO.json: {'operation.approved': 'Operación #{id} aprobada por la constructora {name} el {date}'}. (4) language selection: per user preference or per org country. (5) deploy with toggle. (6) estimated effort: 40-60 hours for extraction + library integration. Translation: additional (per language × per word count × professional translator rate)."
		meshImplication: "String management now: (1) **naming discipline — zero cost, high future value.** Every user-facing string: complete sentence with named placeholders. No: 'Operação #' + id + ' foi ' + status. Yes: 'Operação #{id} foi {status}.' When extracted: placeholder substitution handles all languages regardless of word order. (2) **API errors: code + message structure.** {error_code: 'TAX_ID_INVALID', message: 'CNPJ inválido...', details: {field: 'tax_id'}}. Consumer: code for machine logic, message for human display. When i18n: message generated per locale from code + details. Code: language-independent. Details: structured, language-independent. Only message: locale-dependent. (3) **email/notification templates as separate files.** /templates/pt-BR/operation_approved.html (with placeholders). When i18n: add /templates/es-CO/operation_approved.html. Template engine loads per locale. (4) **do NOT invest now (defer):** i18n library integration (adds build complexity, bundle size, dev overhead for zero current benefit). Translation file creation (no content to translate to). Language toggle UI (no second language). Multi-language testing (nothing to test). These: invest when second language is 6 months away. Premature investment: overhead without users. (5) **CLAUDE.md** — 'user-facing strings: complete sentences with named placeholders ({name}, {value}, {date}). No string concatenation for messages. API errors: return error_code (machine) + message (human). Error messages: specific, actionable, and translatable (no PT-BR idioms that don't translate). Avoid: gírias, expressões idiomáticas, humor cultural.' Anti-pattern: error message 'Deu ruim! Tenta de novo.' — Portuguese slang, untranslatable ('Deu ruim' has no Spanish/English equivalent), unprofessional for financial platform. Better: 'Não foi possível processar a operação. Tente novamente ou contate suporte.' — translatable ('No fue posible procesar la operación. Intente nuevamente o contacte soporte.'), professional, actionable."
		dependsOn: ["il-abstraction-calibration"]
		rationale: "i18n readiness without implementation 2024+. Translation-ready architecture 2024+. Na Mesh now: naming discipline + API error codes + template files = zero cost investment. When second language needed: extraction + library integration = 40-60h manageable. If strings are concatenated fragments with Portuguese idioms: extraction is rewrite nightmare (each string must be found, restructured, tested). Discipline now makes future extraction mechanical."
	},
	{
		id:         "il-business-calendar-abstraction"
		name:       "Abstração de Calendário de Negócios: Dias Úteis, Feriados e Horários por País"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "property"
		reviewCadence: "annual"
		definition: "Financial operations depend critically on business days: settlement (D+1 means 1 business day, not 1 calendar day), document expiry (válido por 30 business days), reporting deadlines (5th business day of month), grace periods (3 business days after due date). Business days vary by country: different holidays (Brazil: 15 national + state holidays. Colombia: 18 national holidays. Mexico: 7 mandatory + variable), different weekends (most LATAM: Sat/Sun. Some Middle Eastern countries: Fri/Sat — relevant if Mesh ever expands beyond LATAM). Conceito de 'business calendar as service' (2024+): interface BusinessCalendar { fun isBusinessDay(date: LocalDate, country: CountryCode): Boolean. fun addBusinessDays(date: LocalDate, days: Int, country: CountryCode): LocalDate. fun countBusinessDays(start: LocalDate, end: LocalDate, country: CountryCode): Int. fun getHolidays(year: Int, country: CountryCode): List<LocalDate>. fun nextBusinessDay(date: LocalDate, country: CountryCode): LocalDate. }. Brazil implementation: weekends = Sat + Sun. National holidays: loaded from data file per year (Carnaval, Tiradentes, Independência, etc — 15 fixed + variable). State holidays: configurable per org location (Rio de Janeiro has additional holidays like São Sebastião Jan 20). Holiday data: JSON file per year, maintained annually before year starts. Source: Banco Central do Brasil publishes official business day calendar."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, business calendar: **Interface:** BusinessCalendar with isBusinessDay, addBusinessDays, countBusinessDays, getHolidays, nextBusinessDay. All methods: require country parameter (even though today only BR). **Brazil implementation:** BrazilBusinessCalendar. Weekends: Sat + Sun. National holidays per year: loaded from /data/holidays/BR/{year}.json. Format: [{date: '2026-02-16', name: 'Carnaval'}, {date: '2026-02-17', name: 'Carnaval'}, ...]. State holidays: optional, per org.state config. Example: org in RJ → additional holidays from /data/holidays/BR-RJ/{year}.json. **Usage throughout system:** settlement date = businessCalendar.addBusinessDays(approvalDate, 1, 'BR') (from TM lens). Document expiry = businessCalendar.addBusinessDays(issueDate, 30, 'BR'). Reporting deadline = businessCalendar.addBusinessDays(firstOfMonth, 5, 'BR'). Day count for pricing = businessCalendar.countBusinessDays(settlementDate, maturityDate, 'BR') (from TM lens day-count). **Expansion seam:** adding Colombia: create /data/holidays/CO/2026.json with Colombian holidays. BusinessCalendar.addBusinessDays(date, 1, 'CO') → uses Colombian calendar. Zero code change — data-driven."
		meshImplication: "Calendar implementation: (1) **BusinessCalendar from day 1 — even Brazil-only.** date.plusDays(1) doesn't know about holidays. Friday + 1 = Saturday. Holiday Thursday + 1 = holiday Friday. BusinessCalendar.addBusinessDays knows: Friday + 1 BD = Monday. Holiday Thursday + 1 BD = Friday (or Monday if Friday is also holiday). Settlement on non-business day = payment fails (bank closed). This is not a nice-to-have — it's correctness for financial operations. (2) **holiday data management** — /data/holidays/{country}/{year}.json. Updated annually before January. Source for Brazil: Banco Central publishes calendar (PTAX calendar). Automated: script fetches BC calendar, converts to JSON. Manual fallback: update JSON file. Versioned in repository. (3) **state-level holidays** — Brazilian states have additional holidays. Org config includes state (org.state = 'RJ'). Holiday resolution: national holidays UNION state holidays. If org is in Rio and RJ has São Sebastião (Jan 20): that day is non-business for this org. If org is in SP: Jan 20 is business day. Calendar: resolves per org.country + org.state. (4) **testing** — test cases: addBusinessDays around every holiday in test year. Around weekends. Year boundary (Dec 31 → Jan 1). Carnaval (Sat-Tue non-business: Mon + 1 BD = Wed, not Tue). Property-based test: for all dates in 2026: addBusinessDays(date, N, 'BR') ALWAYS returns a business day AND is always ≥ date + N calendar days. (5) **for agents** — CLAUDE.md: 'date arithmetic for business operations: use BusinessCalendar.addBusinessDays(). NEVER use date.plusDays() or date + timedelta(days=N) for financial deadlines. Holidays matter — D+1 is 1 business day, not 1 calendar day. Settlement, document expiry, reporting deadlines: ALL use BusinessCalendar.' Anti-pattern: settlement calculated as date + 1 calendar day. Fornecedor approved antecipação Wednesday before Corpus Christi (Thursday holiday). System: Wednesday + 1 = Thursday. Bank: closed (holiday). Payment fails. Fornecedor: 'cadê meu dinheiro?' Support ticket. Manual re-processing on Friday. Trust erosion: 'platform can't even get payment dates right.' BusinessCalendar: Wednesday + 1 BD = Friday (correct). Payment succeeds. Trust preserved."
		dependsOn: ["il-abstraction-calibration"]
		rationale: "Business calendar as service 2024+. Na Mesh financial operations, business day calculation is non-negotiable from day 1. Even Brazil-only: 15+ holidays per year where date.plusDays() is wrong. BusinessCalendar(country): correct from day 1, for every holiday, every weekend, every edge case. Adding country: add holiday data file. Consumer code: zero change. Cost: 4 hours for interface + implementation + 1 year of holiday data. Value: prevents 15+ settlement failures per year from day 1."
	},
	{
		id:         "il-expansion-playbook"
		name:       "Playbook de Expansão: Checklist Sistemático para Adicionar País à Plataforma"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "annual"
		definition: "When expanding to new country: systematic checklist of what needs to be configured/implemented. Conceito de 'country expansion as configuration + implementation' (2024+): if abstractions are in place (Money, TaxId, RegulationEngine, BusinessCalendar, Locale): adding country is mostly configuration (add currency, add holidays, add locale) + country-specific implementations (TaxIdValidator, RegulationEngine, TaxDocumentProcessor). NOT codebase rewrite. Playbook: documented step-by-step with estimated effort per step, prerequisites, responsible party, and test criteria. Conceito de 'dry-run with synthetic country' (2024+): before committing to real expansion: create synthetic country 'XX' with mock data (currency XXC with 0 decimals, tax ID format NIT, 10 random holidays, 3 mock compliance requirements). Run through expansion playbook. Verify: all abstractions work for non-Brazil data. Gaps found in dry-run (Money assumes 2 decimals, TaxId formats with CNPJ mask, RegulationEngine has hardcoded Brazilian rules outside interface): fixed on normal development timeline, not under expansion pressure."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, expansion playbook template (effort assumes abstractions in place): **Step 1 — Currency (2h):** add currency code to CurrencyCode enum. Configure: decimal places (BRL: 2, COP: 0, CLP: 0). Money type: handles automatically (format per decimals). Test: Money operations with new currency. Display: verify formatting (symbol, decimals, separators). **Step 2 — Tax Identity (4h):** implement TaxIdValidator for country's identifier. Data: format spec, check digit algorithm, authority API endpoint. Test: valid/invalid samples from country. **Step 3 — Fiscal Documents (8-20h):** implement TaxDocumentProcessor for country's document types. Parse: extract standard fields from country-specific format. Validate: against authority if applicable. Effort varies: NF-e XML (complex, 54 fields) vs simpler invoices. **Step 4 — Regulatory Engine (16-40h):** implement RegulationEngine for country. Research: compliance requirements, reporting schedule, limits, KYC rules. Configure: rules as config. Implement: country-specific logic. Test: compliance scenarios. Most effort — regulatory research dominates (weeks of legal/domain research, days of engineering). **Step 5 — Business Calendar (2h):** add holiday JSON for country. Configure: weekend days. Test: business day calculations around holidays. **Step 6 — Locale Formatting (2h):** configure: number format, date format, currency format, address format, phone format. Intl API handles most. Test: formatting samples for each type. **Step 7 — UI Strings (20-40h if not done yet):** extract strings to locale files (if not previously done). Translate to target language. Test: all screens in new language (layout, truncation, placeholder substitution). Effort varies by string count. First extraction: 40-60h. Subsequent languages: translation only. **Step 8 — Legal/Contractual (variable, non-engineering):** country-specific contracts, terms of use, privacy policy, regulatory filings. Legal review required. Not engineering workstream — parallel legal workstream. **Total engineering (with abstractions): 54-110 hours (7-14 working days).** **Total engineering (WITHOUT abstractions — retrofit): 400-800 hours (2-4 months).** Ratio: 7-14 days vs 2-4 months. Abstractions pay for themselves on first expansion."
		meshImplication: "Playbook implementation: (1) **documented in mesh-spec** — /guides/expansion-playbook.md. For each step: description, prerequisites (what must be in place), estimated effort (hours), responsible party (engineering, legal, founder), test criteria (how to verify step is complete), dependencies (which steps must complete before this one). (2) **pre-expansion audit** — before committing to new country: run through playbook checklist. For each step: status (ready / needs work / blocked). Identify: total effort estimate. Flag: any step that is blocked (e.g., regulatory research not started). Output: go/no-go decision with realistic timeline. (3) **dry-run with synthetic country** — create country 'XX' for testing: currency XXC (0 decimals — different from BRL's 2, which exposes decimal assumptions), TaxId format NIT (10 digits — different from CNPJ's 14), holidays (10 random dates), regulatory requirements (3 different from Brazil's), language es-XX. Run through each playbook step. Verify: (a) Money(100000, 'XXC').format() → '$100.000' (0 decimals). If shows '1.000,00': gap (decimal places hardcoded). Fix: read from CurrencyConfig. (b) TaxId('9001234567', 'NIT', 'XX'). validate() → passes. format() → '900.123.456-7'. If formats with CNPJ mask (dots/slash/dash for 14 digits): gap. Fix: format per type. (c) regulationEngine.getRequirements('XX', SUPPLIER) → returns XX requirements, not Brazilian. If returns Brazilian: gap (hardcoded outside interface). Fix: move to interface. (d) businessCalendar.addBusinessDays(date, 1, 'XX') → uses XX holidays. If uses Brazilian: gap (country parameter not routed). Fix. (e) formatMoney(Money(100000, 'XXC'), locale_XX) → correct format for XX. If pt-BR format: gap. Fix. All gaps found: fixed on normal timeline (months before real expansion). No pressure. (4) **post-expansion review** — after first real expansion: review playbook. What was harder than expected? What was missing? What took longer? Update playbook. Each subsequent expansion: faster (playbook improves, team learns, patterns established). (5) **investor/board communication** — 'expansion to new LATAM country: 2-3 weeks engineering, 2-6 months regulatory research (parallel). Architecture: ready (validated by dry-run). Bottleneck: regulatory, not engineering.' Confidence: because abstractions are in place and validated."
		dependsOn: ["il-abstraction-calibration", "il-multi-currency-architecture", "il-tax-and-fiscal-identity", "il-locale-aware-formatting", "il-regulatory-jurisdiction-abstraction", "il-string-externalization", "il-business-calendar-abstraction"]
		rationale: "Country expansion as configuration 2024+. Dry-run with synthetic country 2024+. Na Mesh, expansion playbook with abstractions in place: 7-14 days per country. Without abstractions: 2-4 months. Playbook is the ROI proof of i18n abstractions. Dry-run: validates before commitment. Each expansion: faster than previous."
	},
	{
