reasoningProtocol: [
	{question: "Todo valor monetário usa Money type com currency explícita? Ou existem bare decimals que assumem BRL?", reveals: "Se multi-currency é possível sem rewrite — ou se cada decimal no codebase precisará ser encontrado e convertido.", rationale: "Money as first-class type Fowler 2002. Bare decimal: retrofit = weeks. Money type from day 1: retrofit = 0."},
	{question: "Identificadores fiscais usam TaxId(value, type, country)? Ou campos 'cnpj' VARCHAR hardcoded?", reveals: "Se expansão para novo país é additive (novo validator) — ou se rewrite de schema + validação + API.", rationale: "TaxId as pluggable type 2024+. 'cnpj' em 30 tabelas: weeks of rename. TaxId: hours to add new type."},
	{question: "Dates são stored em UTC/DATE canônico? Money em centavos? Formatting é per-locale na presentation layer via Intl API?", reveals: "Se storage é locale-agnostic (portável para qualquer locale) — ou se formatted strings no database (ambíguos, non-calculable).", rationale: "Canonical storage + locale-aware presentation. '25/02/2026' stored as string: dd/mm or mm/dd? Ambiguous. DATE 2026-02-25: unambiguous."},
	{question: "Regras regulatórias estão em RegulationEngine interface com Brazil implementation? Ou hardcoded no business logic?", reveals: "Se adding country = new implementation (additive) — ou se extracting rules from scattered business logic (extractive, painful).", rationale: "Jurisdiction as configuration 2024+. Interface: additive. Hardcoded: extractive. Same effort for 1 country; vastly different for 2nd."},
	{question: "BusinessCalendar é usado para TODA aritmética de dias úteis financeiros? Ou date.plusDays() para settlement e deadlines?", reveals: "Se settlement D+1 = next business day (correct, always) — ou se D+1 = Saturday sometimes (payment fails on holidays).", rationale: "Business calendar: correct from day 1, even for Brazil-only. 15+ holidays/year where plusDays() is wrong."},
	{question: "Abstração é calibrada? Money/TaxId/Regulation/Calendar abstraídos (alto retrofit). UI strings hardcoded (baixo retrofit). Não over-engineered?", reveals: "Se investimento é proportional ao risco — ou se tudo é abstraído (overengineering) ou nada (doomed to expensive rewrite).", rationale: "Strategic abstraction 2024+. Abstract where retrofit is expensive + probability high. Hardcode where cheap. Calibrated."},
	{question: "Expansion playbook existe e é validável? Dry-run com país sintético passaria?", reveals: "Se expansão é planejada e validada — ou se 'we'll figure it out when we get there.'", rationale: "With abstractions + validated playbook: 7-14 days per country. Without: 2-4 months. Difference: planning + abstractions."},
]

meshExamples: [
	{
		id:       "ex-money-type-prevents-rewrite"
		scenario: "Mesh expands to Colombia. Developer discovers: 'valor' column in 35 database tables is NUMERIC(15,2) with no currency field. All business logic (calculations, validations, formatting) assumes BRL. All API responses return bare numbers. Estimated retrofit: 3 weeks."
		analysis: "35 tables × 2 changes each (add currency column + update all queries referencing amount) = 70 schema changes. All business logic that reads 'valor': needs currency context (is this BRL or COP? At what exchange rate?). All API responses: need currency wrapper (breaking change → PE versioning). All tests: need currency parameter. All event schemas: need currency field. 3 weeks minimum: if nothing else is happening and team knows every place money appears."
		recommendation: "**Prevention (what should have been done):** Money type from day 1. Database: BIGINT + CHAR(3) currency. API: {amount: centavos, currency: 'BRL'}. Business logic: Money(amount, currency) with same-currency validation. Cost: 4 hours on day 1. **Retrofit (what must happen now):** (1) Add currency column to all 35 tables: ALTER TABLE x ADD COLUMN currency CHAR(3) DEFAULT 'BRL'. Safe migration (additive, default value). (2) Create Money type in application. Wrap all monetary reads/writes with Money. (3) Update API: all monetary fields → {amount, currency}. This is breaking change for consumers: create API v2 per PE lens. (4) Update business logic: all calculations use Money operators (validate same currency). (5) Update event schemas: add currency field per PE event evolution. (6) Update all tests: include currency in generators and assertions. (7) Total estimate: 3 weeks full-time. **Lesson:** 4 hours of Money type on day 1 would have prevented 3 weeks of retrofit. ROI: 120 hours prevented / 4 hours invested = 30x return."
		principlesApplied: ["ax-01", "ax-03"]
		assumptions: ["35 tables is realistic — depends on system maturity; could be 20-50 for financial platform at expansion stage", "3-week estimate is conservative — could be 4-5 weeks including testing and API version management", "4 hours for Money type setup includes: class, operators, database convention doc, API convention doc, CLAUDE.md update"]
		rationale: "Money as first-class type Fowler 2002. 4 hours prevention vs 3 weeks cure. This is the canonical example of why i18n abstraction pays for itself. Bonus: Money type provides type safety benefits even in single-currency (prevents adding amount + percentage accidentally)."
	},
	{
		id:       "ex-business-calendar-settlement-bug"
		scenario: "Fornecedor approved antecipação on Wednesday before Corpus Christi (Thursday national holiday). System calculates settlement as Wednesday + 1 day = Thursday. Bank: closed (national holiday). Payment instruction rejected. Fornecedor expects payment Thursday. Doesn't receive. Contacts support Friday morning."
		analysis: "date.plusDays(1) doesn't know about holidays. Works correctly ~95% of the time (most days are business days). Fails on ~15 national holidays per year + state holidays + whenever approval falls day before holiday. Each failure: fornecedor confusion → support ticket → manual intervention to re-process on next business day → fornecedor trust erosion ('platform can't even get payment dates right'). At scale: 15 failures/year × N fornecedores × support cost × trust damage. Systemic, not one-off."
		recommendation: "(1) Replace date.plusDays(1) with businessCalendar.addBusinessDays(date, 1, 'BR'). Wednesday before Corpus Christi + 1 BD = Friday (skips Thursday holiday). Correct. (2) BusinessCalendar loads: /data/holidays/BR/2026.json with all 15 national holidays + state holidays per org. (3) Implementation: 2-4 hours (interface + implementation + holiday data file for current year). (4) Test: settlement calculation around EVERY 2026 holiday. Property-based test: for all dates in 2026, addBusinessDays(date, 1, 'BR') is always a business day AND is always ≥ date + 1 calendar day. (5) Display to fornecedor at approval: 'depósito previsto: sexta-feira 14/03/2026' (calculated correctly, accounting for holidays). Fornecedor sees correct date → trust. (6) Monitoring: alert if settlement_date falls on non-business day (should never happen after fix). If triggered: calendar data is wrong or BusinessCalendar has bug. (7) Expansion: when Colombia: add /data/holidays/CO/2026.json. BusinessCalendar.addBusinessDays(date, 1, 'CO') uses Colombian holidays. Zero code change. Configuration only."
		principlesApplied: ["ax-01", "ax-06"]
		assumptions: ["BusinessCalendar with national holidays is sufficient — state holidays add complexity but are configurable", "2-4 hours implementation is realistic — interface + implementation + holiday JSON + tests", "holiday data is reliable from Banco Central — yes, BC publishes official calendar annually"]
		rationale: "BusinessCalendar: correct from day 1, even for Brazil-only. 15 potential settlement failures/year prevented. 2-4 hours implementation. Each failure prevented: support ticket avoided + fornecedor trust preserved. When Colombia: add holiday file, zero code change."
	},
	{
		id:       "ex-regulatory-abstraction-saves-expansion"
		scenario: "Agent implementing compliance check hardcodes in ComplianceService.kt line 47: 'if (operation.type == ANTECIPACAO) { require(certidaoNegativa); require(fgtsRegularidade); require(inssRegularidade); }'. Works perfectly for Brazil. Colombia expansion planned in 18 months."
		analysis: "Hardcoded Brazilian-specific documents in core business logic. When Colombia: (a) certidão negativa doesn't exist in Colombia (Colombian equivalent: certificado de existencia y representación legal). (b) FGTS is Brazilian-only labor fund concept. (c) INSS is Brazilian social security — Colombia has different system. Colombian requirements: completely different document set. These can't be added to same if-block. Options without interface: (a) if (country == 'BR') { ...Brazilian... } else if (country == 'CO') { ...Colombian... } — grows linearly with countries. (b) Fork ComplianceService per country — code duplication. Both: maintenance nightmare at 5+ countries."
		recommendation: "(1) Refactor to RegulationEngine: interface RegulationEngine { fun getComplianceRequirements(country, entityType, operationType): List<ComplianceRequirement> }. (2) BrazilRegulation.getComplianceRequirements('BR', SUPPLIER, ANTECIPACAO): returns [{type: 'certidao_negativa', source: 'receita_federal', required: true}, {type: 'fgts_regularidade', source: 'caixa', required: true}, {type: 'inss_regularidade', source: 'inss', required: true}]. (3) ComplianceService refactored: val requirements = regulationEngine.getComplianceRequirements(org.country, org.type, operation.type). requirements.forEach { req -> validate(org, req) }. Generic loop, country-agnostic. (4) Each requirement: validated by ComplianceValidator interface. CertidaoNegativaValidator: queries Receita Federal. FgtsValidator: queries Caixa. Each: registered for its requirement type. (5) Adding Colombia: create ColombiaRegulation. Returns: [{type: 'certificado_existencia', source: 'camara_comercio'}, ...]. Create: CertificadoExistenciaValidator. Register. ComplianceService: zero changes. (6) Cost of refactoring now: 4-6 hours (extract to interface + implementation — same logic, different location). Cost of refactoring when Colombia is imminent and 20+ more hardcoded rules exist across 15 files: 2-3 weeks. (7) CLAUDE.md update: 'compliance requirements from RegulationEngine, not hardcoded. When adding rule: add to country implementation.'."
		principlesApplied: ["ax-01", "ax-03"]
		assumptions: ["3 compliance requirements is simplified — Brazil has 10+ for full compliance", "interface + 1 implementation is same effort as hardcoded — yes, logic goes into implementation instead of inline", "agent follows CLAUDE.md instruction — needs reinforcement through code review"]
		rationale: "Jurisdiction as configuration 2024+. Interface: same effort as hardcoded for single country (logic is the same, just organized differently). Payoff: 2nd country is additive (create new implementation) not extractive (extract from scattered codebase). 4-6 hours now prevents 2-3 weeks later."
	},
	{
		id:       "ex-expansion-dry-run"
		scenario: "Mesh considering Colombia expansion in 18 months. Founder wants to validate: are abstractions actually ready? Or are there hidden assumptions that will break with non-Brazilian data?"
		analysis: "Abstractions nominally in place: Money type, TaxId, RegulationEngine interface, BusinessCalendar, locale-aware formatting. But: never tested with non-Brazil data. Possible hidden gaps: (a) Money formatting assumes 2 decimal places (COP has 0). (b) TaxId display hardcodes CNPJ mask pattern (dots/slash/dash). (c) RegulationEngine has Brazil-specific helper methods that aren't on the interface. (d) BusinessCalendar implementation ignores country parameter (always uses BR holidays). (e) Date formatting hardcodes dd/mm/yyyy instead of using Intl. Each gap: invisible until real expansion data hits it."
		recommendation: "(1) Create synthetic country 'XX': currency XXC (0 decimal places — maximally different from BRL's 2). TaxId: NIT format (9-10 digits — different from CNPJ's 14). Holidays: 10 random dates in 2026. Regulatory: 3 compliance requirements (different from Brazil's). Language: es-XX (Spanish variant). (2) Run through expansion playbook step by step: **Currency:** Money(100000, 'XXC').format(locale_XX). Expected: '$100.000' (0 decimals, no centavos). If shows 'XXC 1.000,00': gap — decimal places hardcoded to 2. Fix: Money.format reads decimal places from CurrencyConfig per currency. **TaxId:** TaxId('9001234567', 'NIT', 'XX'). validate() should pass. format() should show '900.123.456-7'. If formats with CNPJ mask '90.012.345/67--': gap — formatting hardcoded per CNPJ pattern. Fix: format dispatch per TaxIdType. **Regulatory:** regulationEngine.getRequirements('XX', SUPPLIER). Should return XX requirements. If returns Brazilian requirements: gap — engine doesn't dispatch by country (or XX implementation missing). Fix: implement XxRegulation + register. **Calendar:** businessCalendar.addBusinessDays(date_near_XX_holiday, 1, 'XX'). Should skip XX holiday. If uses Brazilian holidays regardless: gap — country parameter ignored. Fix: route by country. **Formatting:** formatDate(date, locale_XX). Should format per Spanish convention. If pt-BR regardless: gap — Intl not using locale. Fix: pass locale to Intl API. (3) Document all gaps found. Fix each (small PRs, normal priority — 18 months available). Re-run dry-run after fixes: all pass. (4) Total dry-run effort: 16-24 hours (create synthetic data, run through, investigate gaps, document findings). Fixing gaps: 8-20 hours depending on how many. Total investment: 24-44 hours, spread over weeks. (5) Result: when Colombia expansion actually happens: confidence that engineering is 2 weeks, not 2 months. Gaps: already fixed. Playbook: validated."
		principlesApplied: ["ax-01", "ax-03", "ax-07"]
		assumptions: ["synthetic country with 0 decimals exposes more gaps than similar-decimal currency — correct, 0 is maximally different from 2", "16-24 hours for dry-run is sufficient — for well-structured codebase with abstractions nominally in place", "18 months lead time allows comfortable fix schedule — yes, no pressure", "gaps found in dry-run are representative of real expansion gaps — synthetic country designed to be maximally different from Brazil tests worst-case"]
		rationale: "Expansion playbook dry-run: validates abstractions with real (synthetic) data before commitment. Gaps found: fixed on normal development timeline (18 months). Gaps found during actual expansion: fixed under pressure (weeks). Dry-run cost: 24-44 hours. Benefit: confidence that expansion = 2 weeks engineering, backed by evidence."
	},
]

