limitations: [
	{description: "Abstracting before having real second-country data risks building wrong abstractions — what generalizes for Colombia may not fit Mexico.", alternative: "Abstractions are based on well-understood LATAM patterns: Money, TaxId, BusinessCalendar, Regulation are fundamental across all LATAM countries. Risk of wrong abstraction: low for these fundamentals. Higher risk: domain-specific abstractions (what is 'antecipação' called in Colombia? What vehicle replaces FIDC?). Mitigate: validate abstractions with LATAM fintech research. Dry-run with synthetic country catches structural issues. Domain specifics: research when expansion is concrete.", rationale: "Fundamental abstractions (money, tax ID, calendar): well-understood, low risk. Domain-specific (regulatory details, vehicle types): research before committing."},
	{description: "Maintaining abstractions (Money type, TaxId, interfaces) when 100% of users are Brazilian adds development overhead.", alternative: "Overhead is minimal: wrapper type adds ~10% code volume to financial logic. But: type safety benefit is IMMEDIATE even without expansion. Money type prevents: adding amount + tax_rate accidentally (different units, both Long). TaxId prevents: 13-digit CNPJ passing validation (caught by format check). BusinessCalendar prevents: settlement on holiday (caught from day 1). Abstractions pay for themselves in type safety BEFORE any expansion.", rationale: "Overhead: minimal (~10% code volume). Type safety benefit: immediate. Net: positive even if expansion never happens."},
	{description: "UI string externalization (i18n library, translation files) is expensive (40-60h) and premature for 0 non-Portuguese users.", alternative: "Defer string externalization until second language is 6 months away. Invest now: naming discipline (complete sentences, no concatenation = zero cost). API error codes (machine-readable = zero cost). Template files per locale path (zero cost until second locale). When second language justified: extraction + library = 40-60h, manageable in 2-week sprint.", rationale: "Defer implementation, prepare architecture. Naming discipline now: makes future extraction mechanical. Extraction without discipline: rewrite."},
	{description: "Exchange rate management for multi-currency is complex (rate sources, timing, FX risk, regulatory compliance, hedging).", alternative: "Defer exchange rate implementation until multi-currency is active. Architectural seam: ExchangeRateService interface exists. Implementation: throws UnsupportedOperationException. When needed: implement with rate source (Banco Central), audit trail, rate-locking logic, and FX risk policy. Architecture: ready (interface exists). Implementation: deferred (no unnecessary complexity).", rationale: "Exchange rates: genuinely complex, genuinely unnecessary until multi-currency. Interface seam: ready. Implementation: when needed. Zero premature complexity."},
	{description: "Regulatory research for new country is expensive and slow — requires lawyer, domain expert, and regulatory mapping. Cannot be automated or parallelized with engineering.", alternative: "Engineering and regulatory are parallel workstreams with different timelines. Engineering: abstractions ready (validated by dry-run) in 2 weeks. Regulatory: research, legal mapping, contract templates in 2-6 months (country-dependent). Bottleneck: regulatory research, NOT engineering. Expansion planning: start regulatory research 6-12 months before engineering work. When regulatory is complete: engineering executes in 2 weeks using playbook.", rationale: "Engineering: fast (abstractions ready, playbook validated). Regulatory: slow (research, legal review, compliance mapping). Both: parallel. Bottleneck: regulatory, not engineering. Plan accordingly."},
]

rationale: "A ambição da Mesh é ser a maior empresa da América Latina — o que significa múltiplas moedas (BRL, COP, MXN, CLP), múltiplos regimes regulatórios (Bacen/CVM, SFC, CNBV, BCRA), múltiplos idiomas (pt-BR, es-LATAM), e múltiplos formatos fiscais (CNPJ, NIT, RFC, CUIT, RUT) coexistindo na mesma plataforma. Decisões de i18n são arquiteturais e extremamente caras de retrofit. Na Mesh, esta lens operacionaliza: calibração de abstração entre YAGNI e custo de retrofit (Beck 1999, Lehman 1980, strategic abstraction 2024+, architectural seam 2023+), Money como tipo de primeira classe com currency explícita (Fowler 2002, currency-aware calculation 2024+, exchange rate management 2024+), TaxId como tipo pluggable com validação por interface (tax identifier pluggable 2024+, fiscal document abstraction 2024+), formatação locale-aware com storage canônico e presentation por Intl API (locale as runtime context 2024+), abstração de jurisdição regulatória com RegulationEngine interface (jurisdiction as configuration 2024+, regulatory feature flags 2024+), externalização de strings com preparação de naming discipline sem implementação prematura (i18n readiness without implementation 2024+, translation-ready architecture 2024+), calendário de negócios como serviço por país (business calendar as service 2024+), e playbook de expansão com dry-run de país sintético (country expansion as configuration 2024+). Upfront investment: ~20-30 horas de abstrações fundamentais. Prevented retrofit na primeira expansão: 400-800 horas. ROI: 15-30x. Abstract where expensive to retrofit (Money, TaxId, Regulation, Calendar). Defer where cheap to retrofit (UI strings). Validate with dry-run before commitment."

}
